# MLB Betting Workbench for Beginners

A plain-English MLB betting package that combines:

- **historical truth** from Retrosheet season zip files
- **live sportsbook prices** from DraftKings captures
- **per-zip historical caching** so you do not re-process every archive every run

## Main output files

### Historical results
- `player-directory.parquet`
- `actual-game-results.parquet`
- `actual-team-game-results.parquet`
- `actual-hitter-stats-by-game.parquet`
- `actual-pitcher-stats-by-game.parquet`

### DraftKings lines
- `draftkings-mlb-lines.parquet`
- `draftkings-mlb-game-lines.parquet`
- `draftkings-mlb-player-props.parquet`
- `draftkings-mlb-priced-board.parquet`

## Historical cache

Historical parsing is cached under:

- `.cache/historical/`

Each zip file gets its own cache folder.

The cache key for each zip is built from:
- zip file name
- file size
- modified time

If only one season file changes, only that season is rebuilt.
The final output tables are then recombined from the cached season slices.

Use `--force-rebuild` to ignore cache and rebuild every zip.

## What the priced board adds

- long decimal probability fields
- decimal odds
- properly signed American odds like `+150` or `-120`
- a clean display label like:
  - `Over 1.500`
  - `Under 1.500`
  - `Yes`
  - `No`
  - `Home`
  - `Away`

## Install

```bash
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e .
```

## Build historical data from Retrosheet zips

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli build-historical-betting-data \
  --zip-dir /path/to/zips \
  --out-dir artifacts
```

Force a full rebuild:

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli build-historical-betting-data \
  --zip-dir /path/to/zips \
  --out-dir artifacts \
  --force-rebuild
```

## Build DraftKings MLB files from saved JSON or HTML captures

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli build-draftkings-mlb-board \
  --capture-file /path/to/capture1.json \
  --capture-file /path/to/capture2.html \
  --out-dir artifacts
```

## Build DraftKings MLB files from live capture

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli build-draftkings-mlb-board \
  --use-live-capture \
  --out-dir artifacts
```


## Display style

- Short, readable numbers only
  - `52.4%` instead of `0.523947`
  - `1.91` instead of `1.909876`
  - `+150` and `-120` for American odds
- Proper betting symbols when needed
- Plain-English file names and column names
- Beginner bettor wording in reports


## History-trained model pipeline

This version adds a real **history-trained player-performance model** pipeline.

What it can train from the historical results files:
- hitter props:
  - hits
  - total bases
  - home runs
  - runs scored
  - runs batted in
  - walks
  - strikeouts
  - stolen bases
- pitcher props:
  - strikeouts
  - outs recorded
  - earned runs
  - hits allowed
  - walks allowed
  - home runs allowed

What it writes:
- `history trained model summary.csv`
- `latest player form.parquet`
- `player prop fair prices.parquet`
- `best bets.csv`

Important:
- this is **history-trained on player performance**
- it is **not yet history-trained on old sportsbook prices**
- that means it can learn what players usually do, then compare that to a current prop board
- but it still does not learn bookmaker mistakes from an archive of old book prices, because those old prices were not uploaded here

## Train the models

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli train-history-models --out-dir artifacts
```

This expects these files to already exist in the same `out-dir`:
- `actual hitter stats by game.parquet`
- `actual pitcher stats by game.parquet`
- `player directory.parquet`

## Score a player prop board

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli score-player-prop-board   --board-file "artifacts/draftkings mlb player props.parquet"   --out-dir artifacts
```

This writes:
- `player prop fair prices.parquet`
- `best bets.csv`


## Team and game models

This version adds **history-trained team and game models** too.

What it can now learn from historical team and game results:
- team to win
- game total runs
- home team runs
- away team runs
- run line style win margin
- team total runs

What it writes:
- `latest team form.parquet`
- `game fair prices.parquet`
- `game best bets.csv`

What "fully history-trained" means here:
- the player models learn from past hitter and pitcher game results
- the team and game models learn from past team and game results
- both are trained using past seasons only and tested on later seasons

Important:
- this is now **fully history-trained for player performance and team or game performance**
- it is still **not fully history-trained on old sportsbook prices**
- that means it learns what usually happens in real games, then compares that to the current board
- it still does not learn bookmaker mistakes from an archive of old game and prop prices, because those old prices were not uploaded here

## Score a game board

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli score-game-board   --board-file "artifacts/draftkings mlb game lines.parquet"   --out-dir artifacts
```

This writes:
- `game fair prices.parquet`
- `game best bets.csv`


## Build your own odds archive from now on

This version adds a real **DraftKings archive** layer.

What it does:
- saves every raw DraftKings capture with a timestamp
- saves the normalized MLB lines for that same timestamp
- saves separate files for:
  - game lines
  - player props
  - priced board
  - beginner betting report
- rebuilds one combined historical archive file from all saved snapshots

Why this matters:
- you stop losing old prices
- you can backtest later
- you can compare today's line to how it moved earlier in the day
- you can slowly build the missing old price history yourself from now on

## Archive files

Inside your output folder, this package writes:

- `archive/draftkings/raw/YYYY/MM/DD/HHMMSSZ/`
- `archive/draftkings/boards/YYYY/MM/DD/HHMMSSZ/`
- `draftkings mlb archive history.parquet`
- `draftkings mlb archive history.csv`

## Save one snapshot

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli capture-draftkings-snapshot \
  --use-live-capture \
  --out-dir artifacts
```

Or from saved files:

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli capture-draftkings-snapshot \
  --capture-file /path/to/capture1.json \
  --capture-file /path/to/capture2.html \
  --out-dir artifacts
```

## Rebuild the combined archive

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli rebuild-draftkings-history --out-dir artifacts
```

## Simple daily habit

A very practical setup is:
- save one snapshot in the morning
- save one snapshot around lineup time
- save one snapshot close to first pitch

That slowly builds a real line history you can train against later.


Patched in 1.0.2:
- better player-name matching
- safer game scoring fallback when team features are missing
- probability clamp to stop garbage fair prices
- stronger alias support for common DraftKings MLB prop names


## FanDuel and multi-book comparison

This version adds FanDuel beside DraftKings.

What it adds:
- FanDuel capture from JSON, HTML, or live requests
- FanDuel board files
- FanDuel archive snapshots
- combined two-book comparison files
- best-price view across DraftKings and FanDuel

New commands:

```bash
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli build-fanduel-mlb-board --capture-file /path/to/fanduel.json --out-dir artifacts
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli capture-fanduel-snapshot --use-live-capture --out-dir artifacts
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli rebuild-fanduel-history --out-dir artifacts
python -m mlb_betting_data.cli compare-mlb-books --out-dir artifacts
```

New output files:
- `fanduel mlb lines.parquet`
- `fanduel mlb game lines.parquet`
- `fanduel mlb player props.parquet`
- `fanduel mlb priced board.parquet`
- `fanduel mlb betting report.csv`
- `fanduel mlb archive history.parquet`
- `fanduel mlb archive history.csv`
- `mlb two book comparison.parquet`
- `mlb two book comparison.csv`
- `mlb best price by market.parquet`
- `mlb best price by market.csv`


## FanDuel MLB filter fix

This version fixes FanDuel MLB filtering so non-MLB events do not leak into MLB comparison outputs.


## FanDuel 1.1.3 fix

This version fixes FanDuel same-player prop comparison so FanDuel `to hit a home run` rows normalize to `selection = yes` and line-shop correctly against DraftKings.
